    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-01-27T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-01-27T03:00:00-05:00" n="651"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/8032: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-01-27T17:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1921—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 27—2:53 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>41. My 34 [<hi rend="italic">35</hi>], January 22, 4 p.m.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d651fn2">Not printed.</note> In reply to interpellations during the
                    opening debates of the Diet Premier Hara after reviewing the history of Siberian
                    expedition and the reasons for the retention up to the present time of Japanese
                    troops in Vladivostok and vicinity, stated that in order to prevent the
                    disturbed conditions in Siberia from affecting Japan troops must be retained
                    there until tranquillity is restored.</p>
                <p>The Minister of War in reply to an interpellation in connection with the shooting
                    of Lieutenant Langdon<note n="3" xml:id="d651fn3">See <ref target="#pg_354">pp.
                            354</ref> ff.</note> stated that although it had not yet been determined
                    who was the first to shoot, he doubted whether it was the Japanese sentry. He
                    added that in compliance with the request of the dean of the consular corps in
                    Vladivostok the Japanese forces had been taking steps to preserve order
                    there.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
